================================================================================
 Ganeti Web Manager
================================================================================

Ganeti Web Manager is a Django based web application that allows administrators
and clients access to their ganeti clusters.  

http://code.osuosl.org/projects/ganeti-webmgr


================================================================================
 Installation
================================================================================

1.  Install Dependencies
    * Django
    * django-registration
    * object_permissions (packaged with releases)

2. Deploy this code somewhere.
3. Copy settings.py.dist to settings.py
4. Create a database and configure your settings:

 DATABASE_ENGINE = ''   <-- Change This to 'mysql', 'postgresql', 'postgresql_psycopg2' or 'oracle'
 DATABASE_NAME = ''     <-- Change This
 DATABASE_USER = ''     <-- Change This
 DATABASE_PASSWORD = '' <-- Change This
 DATABASE_HOST = ''     <-- Change this (not needed if database is localhost)
 DATABASE_PORT = ''     <-- Change this (not needed if database is localhost)

5. Initialize the databse

    ./manage.py syncdb

6. run the server

    Development: ./manage.py runserver
    Production:  follow the guides on django-project.com for configuring Apache
    
    http://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.2/howto/deployment/
    

================================================================================
 Creating a Cluster
================================================================================

1. Use the admin user created during syncdb to log in.
2. Create a cluster:  Clusters -> Add Cluster
3. When the cluster is created it will automatically synchronize the list of
Virtual Machines with information from the ganeti cluster.


================================================================================
 Users, Groups, and Permissions
================================================================================

Permissions may be granted on clusters and virtual machines.  This allows access
for any part of the cluster to be controlled

Clusters:
  1. Clusters -> Cluster -> User
  2. Click permissions for existing user, or add for a new user
  3. edit and save.

Virtual Machines:
  1. Virtual Machines -> Virtual Machine -> User
  2. Click permissions for existing user, or add for a new user
  3. edit and save
  

Users may belong to any number of user groups.  User groups can be assigned
permissions and quotas just like users.  Users inherit permissions from groups
and may act on their behalf to create virtual machines.


================================================================================
 Assigning Quotas
================================================================================

NOTE: quotas can be edited but they are not restricting usage, yet.

Cluster quotas will restrict how much resources a User or Group can consume.  A
default quota can be assigned to a cluster, which will affect all users and
groups.  This can be overridden by:

   1. Clusters -> Cluster -> Users
   2. click on the quota
   3. edit values

entering no values for the quota grants unlimited amount of that resource.


================================================================================
 Orphaned VirtualMachines
================================================================================

You can find VirtualMachines with no permissions via Admin -> Orphaned VMs.
This will force a synchronization of all clusters and display VirtualMachines
that do not have any permissions assigned.

You only need to grant permissions directly on virtual machines if you are
granting access to non-admin users.






